M., with 75 passengers, and a larger assorted freight than usual, consisting of dry goods, cotton, wool, flour, and leather. There were only 15 ladies among the passengers, and fortunately only four children; the remainder were gentlemen, many of them being well-known merchants belonging to Providence and Boston. The freight was mostly consigned to Providence.
